{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5a5df196-bbf0-4e29-867e-118b968d604d","content":"Yes, both approaches are correct for .NET MAUI on .NET 10.\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This is the standard iOS platform-specific that insets your page content to avoid the notch/Dynamic Island. You need the namespace:\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n```\n\nThen on your `ContentPage`:\n\n```xml\nios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"\n```\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This lets a specific view (like a Grid with a background image) extend *beyond* the safe area, even when the page itself respects it. This is the correct pattern for full-bleed backgrounds while keeping other content safely inset.\n\nTypical pattern:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage ... ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n  <Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n    <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n    <!-- Other content stays within safe area -->\n    <StackLayout Padding=\"20\" ... />\n  </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nBoth APIs are stable and remain the recommended approach in .NET 10 MAUI.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e6586018-40ba-472e-bb25-1f08265aec3c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - a property on Grid for background images\n\nLet me check what I know about these APIs in .NET MAUI, particularly for .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the iOS safe area handling has evolved. Let me think about this:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` - This is a platform-specific property from Xamarin.Forms that was carried over to .NET MAUI. In .NET MAUI, the iOS platform-specific for safe area on a Page is `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`.\n\n\n2. For `IgnoreSafeArea`, I need to verify what's available in the current .NET MAUI version. The `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific.Page.UseSafeArea` is the documented platform-specific for handling safe areas on iOS pages, and there's also discussion around `IgnoreSafeArea` for specific views that need to extend beyond safe area boundaries. I'm confident both approaches are valid for .NET MAUI through .NET 10—`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` controls whether the page respects the safe area, while `IgnoreSafeArea` on specific views lets them extend beyond it when needed.","outputTokens":1155,"requestId":"E829:1801E:139FD8C:1634280:69F94345"},"id":"83b991e9-7832-4e73-8dfb-b8b420ae1a84","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:09:48.074Z","parentId":"3cbdb677-b0df-4128-8485-ea4d90c85270"}
